# timedatectl – Modern Date/Time Management in systemd

## Purpose
- `timedatectl` is a systemd utility for viewing & configuring:
  - Date
  - Time
  - Time zones
  - NTP synchronization
- Replaces the older `date` command (both coexist for now).
- Works with:
  - `chronyd` (modern NTP daemon)
  - `ntpd` (older NTP daemon)
  - `systemd-timesyncd` (lightweight systemd time sync daemon – not in default RHEL/CentOS repos)

---

## Basic Usage
- **Check system time & sync status**
  ```bash
  timedatectl
  timedatectl status

Shows:

    Local time

    Universal time (UTC)

    RTC (hardware clock)

    Time zone

    NTP enabled & synchronized status

    DST (Daylight Saving Time) info

Time Zone Management

    List available time zones

timedatectl list-timezones

(Press space to scroll, q to quit)

Set time zone

sudo timedatectl set-timezone "Region/City"

Example:

    sudo timedatectl set-timezone "America/New_York"

Setting Date & Time

    Set date only

sudo timedatectl set-time YYYY-MM-DD

Set date & time

    sudo timedatectl set-time "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS"

    (24-hour format recommended)

NTP Synchronization

    Enable automatic time sync

sudo timedatectl set-ntp true

Disable automatic time sync

    sudo timedatectl set-ntp false

Integration with NTP Daemons

    Check if NTP daemon is running

systemctl status chronyd
systemctl status ntpd

If inactive, start & enable

    sudo systemctl enable --now chronyd

    timedatectl will sync to the active daemon.

Key Points

    timedatectl is part of systemd (CentOS 7+, RHEL 7+).

    Eventually replaces date command for system time control.

    systemd-timesyncd is lightweight but not shipped by default in RHEL/CentOS.

    Always verify NTP daemon status if sync fails.

    Restart NTP service after configuration changes.

